</taxonomicName>
species group
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[264,1324,759,1025]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
The two species of this group, representing the only previously described species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Myrsidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<taxonomicName box="[439,574,799,825]" class="Aves" family="Tyrannidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Tyrannidae</taxonomicName>
, are characterized as having both sexes with a much larger number of abdominal tergal and/or sternal setae than any other known species from this family. The females have only a modest enlargement of the anterior abdominal tergites (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 2" captionStartId="3.[264,383,1728,1752]" captionTargetBox="[272,1322,287,1711]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[260,1327,281,1713]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 8. 1 – 2, Myrsidea magnidens. 1, Female metanotum and dorsal abdomen. 2, Male genital sac sclerite. 3, M. stenodesma female metanotum and dorsal abdomen. 4 – 6, M. pitangi. 4, Female metanotum and dorsoventral abdomen. 5, Entire dorsoventral male. 6, Male genitalia. 7, M. seversoni female dorsal thorax and abdomen. 8, M. melancholici female dorsal thorax and abdomen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/169923/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Figs. 1, 3</figureCitation>
). Although the host identities of both species are uncertain, this group is morphologically distinctive from other 
<taxonomicName box="[596,707,959,984]" class="Insecta" family="Menoponidae" genus="Myrsidea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phthiraptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[596,707,959,984]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Myrsidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with known host associations with the 
<taxonomicName class="Aves" family="Tyrannidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Tyrannidae</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
